{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17500157","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17500157"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:10:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:10:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1618"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1618","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1618"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.15,0.14,0.57,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1618"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"31707"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1618","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1618"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1618"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"17465"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"867"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6865"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7898"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"31707","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/31707"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 83-year-old man has presented with symptoms suggestive of a problem in his neck. His general practitioner has organised a barium swallow (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"With which one of the following symptoms would he have most likely presented?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Swelling in the neck","Rapid onset of dysphagia and weight loss","Difficulty in swallowing liquids","Spitting back food particles immediately after swallowing","Hoarseness of voice"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThere is a collection of contrast in the upper oesophagus. This is pooled in a pharyngeal pouch - otherwise known as a Zenker\u0027s diverticulum. These patients can present with a variety of symptoms and most will have some degree of dysphagia - but these symptoms tend to be long-standing, with the patients typically waiting several years before seeking advice. Food particles and tablets will often get stuck in the diverticulum, with the patient \u0027coughing\u0027 or \u003Cstrong\u003Espitting the material back soon after eating\u003C/strong\u003E. Aspiration of foodstuffs is also common.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESwelling in the neck\u003C/strong\u003E may be due to enlarged lymph nodes secondary to malignancy or cancer, or due to an enlarged thyroid or goitre. A Zenker\u0027s diverticulum does not have any mass effect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERapid onset dysphagia and weight loss\u003C/strong\u003E are two red flags that would raise suspicion for an oesophageal cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDifficulty in swallowing liquids\u003C/strong\u003E occurs due to achalasia which is characterised by a progressive dysphagia from solids to liquids as disease severity increases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHoarseness of voice\u003C/strong\u003E is most commonly due to compression of the recurrent laryngeal nerve. A Zenker\u0027s diverticulum is unlikely to cause such a compression.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Patients with a Zenker\u0027s diverticulum often present with dysphagia, regurgitation of undigested, solid food and halitosis"],"references":["Law R, Katzka DA, Baron TH. Zenker\u2019s Diverticulum. Clinical Gastroenterology and Hepatology 2014; 12:1773\u201382."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"17465"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1618"}},"s